  "prompt": "What's the difference between a degree in Computer Science & Engineering, a degree in Computer Engineering, and a degree in EECS?",
  "response": "Let me break down the differences:\n\nComputer Science & Engineering (CS&E):\n- Focuses on both software and hardware\n- More theoretical and broad-based\n- Strong programming skills\n- Deeper understanding of computer systems\n- Typically covers algorithms, software design, hardware architecture\n- Can lead to roles like software engineer, system architect\n\nComputer Engineering (CE):\n- More hardware-focused\n- Emphasizes electrical engineering principles\n- Strong focus on computer hardware design\n- Embedded systems, digital logic, microprocessors\n- Less software-intensive than CS\n- Good for roles in hardware design, embedded systems engineering\n\nElectrical Engineering & Computer Science (EECS):\n- Interdisciplinary degree\n- Combines electrical engineering and computer science\n- Very broad curriculum\n- Deep technical knowledge across both domains\n- Flexibility to specialize in hardware or software\n- Prepares for roles in diverse technical fields\n- Often offered at schools with strong engineering programs\n\nKey Differences:\n- CS&E: More balanced software/hardware\n- CE: More hardware-focused\n- EECS: Most interdisciplinary, broadest scope\n\nThe specific curriculum can vary between universities, so it's always best to check individual program details.",
